Problem Statement¶

The majority of AllLife Bank's customers are deposit-only. Few of them, though, take out personal loans. The bank wants to convert more depositors into loan customers without losing them as depositors because loans generate more interest revenue.

The success percentage of a campaign last year was 9%, which was encouraging. To increase this success rate, the marketing team wants to use targeted campaigns to improve this success rate.

As a Data Scientist, your role is to build a model that predicts which customers are most likely to accept a personal loan, so that the marketing team can focus efforts on those high-potential customers.

Objective¶

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and to identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Age of customer
  • Experience: Years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code
  • Family: Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level - 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate; 3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage (if any) (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? *nOnline: Do customers use Internet banking facilities?
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All Life Bank)?

In [21]:
# removal of outliers

def remove_outliers(df, column, threshold):
  outliers = df[df[column] <= threshold]

  sns.boxplot(outliers[column])
  plt.title("Boxplot without Outliers")
  plt.show()
  return outliers

columns = ['Income', 'CCAvg', 'Mortgage']
threshold = [150, 7, 500]
no_outliers = remove_outliers(df, columns, threshold)

Observation:

The income data does not have any outliers while the CCAvg have minor outliers and mortgage has outliers in its upper end.

In [26]:
# Feature Engineering

dfe = df.copy()

dfe['Income_per_CCAvg'] = dfe['Income'] / (dfe['CCAvg'] + 1)    # Income per Credit Card Average Spend

dfe['Income_to_Mortgage'] = dfe['Income'] / (dfe['Mortgage'] + 1)   # Income to Mortgage Ratio

dfe['CCAvg_to_Mortgage'] = dfe['CCAvg'] / (dfe['Mortgage'] + 1)   # Credit Card Average to Mortgage Ratio

binary_columns = ['Personal_Loan', 'CreditCard', 'Online', 'Securities_Account']
for col in binary_columns:
    dfe[col] = dfe[col].map({0: 'No', 1: 'Yes'})

print("New features: ", dfe.columns.tolist())

Data Preparation¶

In [62]:
# defining features and targets
X = df.drop(columns=["Personal_Loan"])
y = df["Personal_Loan"]

X = pd.get_dummies(X, drop_first=True)    # creating dummy variables

X = X.astype(int)

# splitting the dataset into train and test
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X,    # specifying independent variables
    y,    # specifying dependent variables
    test_size=0.2,    # specifying the size of the test set
    stratify = y,   # ensures that training and test set have similar distribution of response variable
    random_state=42)    # specifying the seed value to enable reproducible results

Observation:

  • The target variable is the Personal_Loan and other columns are the features.
  • The dataset is split into traning anf test set with a ratio of 80:20 and it ensures reproductibility of results at a random_state of 42.

In [105]:

print("F1 Score:", f1_score(y_test, y_pred))    # to compute f1-score
print("Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

Model Performance Comparison and Final Model Selection¶

In [214]:
# defining function to check the performance of the model
def model_performance_classification(model, predictors, target):
  pred = model.predict(predictors)

  acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)      # compting accuracy
  prec = precision_score(target, pred)    # compting precision
  rec = recall_score(target, pred)        # compting recall
  f1 = f1_score(target, pred)             # compting f1-score

  # creating dataframe of metrics
  df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
      {'Accuracy':acc, 'Precision':prec, 'Recall':rec, 'F1-Score':f1,},index=[0],)

  return df_perf

Observation:

  • The Income and Education are highly influential attributes in determining the Loan purchasing by the customer.

Key takeaways for the marketing team¶

  • Among the three decision tree classifier models, the model of the pre-pruning tree (dtree2) gives the best accuracy of 0.990, precision of 0.938, recall of 0.958 and f1-score of 0.948.
  • The unpruned decision tree of before pruning has 100% accuracy on the training data but it indicates the overfitting.
  • The correlation between the income and credit card average spending is strong positive correlation (0.65).
  • From the pairplot, we can confirm that the customers with higher income levels are likely to accept the personal loans when compared to those with lower income.
  • The undergrads have higher income distribution when compared to the graduate and professional.
  • An average portion of loan acceptors use online banking and credit card features and this depicts that these customers would be comfortable in using the digital communication.

Advice on how to do this campaign¶

  • The final model (dtree2) can be used efficiently to filter out the customers for the loan acceptance. This can also include people with higher income and undergrads.
  • Awareness campaigns could be conducted in order to spread awareness to the people on how to use the personal loan effectively especially among people with lower income.
  • The credit card benefits could be improved or added to the customers who have personal loans and this would help in enhancing their current loan service.
  • New plans with better rate of interest or EMI plans can be given to the customers who previously rejected the personal loans.
  • Customized marketing strategies could be implemented such as offering education loan to customers with undergrad or graduate or early professionals.
  • Digital campaigns should be promoted in order to encourage online banking and promotion of personal loans can be made via emails, app notifications or messages.

Conclusion¶

  • The customers with the higher income are more likely to accept the personal loan.
  • Undergrads have higher income than graduates and professionals.
  • There are no missing values or duplicate values in the dataset which significantly makes the model efficient and reliable.
  • Outliers are present in mortgage and CCAvg but they do not affect the model's performance.
  • Families of size 2 have higher income when compared to the other families.
  • The pre-pruned decision tree model is best in performance and it has high accuracy, precision, recall and f1-score.

Business Recommendations¶

  • The target customers must be the ones with high income and undergrad education level as they are the major loan acceptors.
  • Avoid spending campaign budgets on customers with low income unless they show interest in getting the loan.
  • Provide multiple offers to undergrads, graduates, early professionals in such a way of offering low interest rate on loans or providing additional benefits.
  • Focus on customers with family size 2 as they are loan acceptors. Also provide additional loan benefits to customers of family size 3 and 4.
  • Update the model with the campaign results regularly and seasonally in order to attract more number of customers to get the personal loans.
  • Promote exclusive personal loans to customers who use only All Life Bank's credit card.
